The integration of Acumatica ERP with Microsoft Active Directory (AD) provides centralized management of users and access. After integration, your domain users can use their domain user names and passwords to sign in to Acumatica ERP. You can set up integration with AD if Acumatica ERP is installed in your organization&rsquo;s intranet. If your Acumatica ERP instance is deployed in the external network, you must use Active Directory Federation Services to provide access to the system for your domain users. For details, see [HelpRoot_Integration\US__con_ADFS_Integration|Integration with AD FS].{br}
You create, delete, and manage user accounts by using Active Directory. Users&rsquo; access rights to Acumatica ERP are determined based on the mapping rules between AD groups and Acumatica ERP roles.{br}
This chapter describes the configuration and management of Acumatica ERP integration with Active Directory. ==In This Chapter==[anchor|#ul_t1p_cjz_4p] *[HelpRoot_Integration\US__con_Integration_with_Active_Directory|Integration with Active Directory] *[HelpRoot_Integration\US__how_Active_Directory_Integration__Enable|To Enable Active Directory Integration] *[HelpRoot_Integration\US__how_Active_Directory_Integration__Map_Roles|To Map Active Directory Groups to Roles in Acumatica ERP] *[HelpRoot_Integration\US__how_AD_Groups_Override|To Set Up Role Assignment for Domain Users]

You integrate Acumatica ERP with Microsoft Active Directory (AD) to manage users and access in one place. You create, delete, and manage user accounts by using AD. During integration you map AD groups with user roles in Acumatica ERP to determine users&rsquo; access rights.((({S:Hint}Enabling integration with AD does not affect the standard authorization and authentication mechanism of Acumatica ERP. With the AD integration enabled, you still can create regular (non-AD) users in Acumatica ERP. ))){br}{TOC} ==Configuration Steps== To integrate an instance of Acumatica ERP with AD, you perform the following steps:[anchor|#ol_a41_bnd_vl] #Enable integration with Active Directory by modifying the <tt>web.config</tt> file of the application instance, as described in [HelpRoot_Integration\US__how_Active_Directory_Integration__Enable|To Enable Active Directory Integration]. #:((({S:Warn}When you save changes to the <tt>web.config</tt> file, the website is automatically restarted. Make sure that all users are warned about the restart so that they can save their documents in advance. ))) #Map the user roles configured in Acumatica ERP to the groups configured in the Active Directory domain by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_05|User Roles] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201005|SM201005]) form in Acumatica ERP. For details, see [HelpRoot_Integration\US__how_Active_Directory_Integration__Map_Roles|To Map Active Directory Groups to Roles in Acumatica ERP]. #:((({S:Hint}Enabling AD integration does not affect the standard authorization and authentication capabilities of Acumatica ERP. With AD integration enabled, you can still create internal users in Acumatica ERP. ))) #Optional: If you need to override roles assigned to AD users, manually add the AD user accounts to the system (if necessary) and specify the roles for the accounts. For details, see [HelpRoot_Integration\US__how_AD_Groups_Override|To Set Up Role Assignment for Domain Users]. [anchor|#_f94f5b31-9b32-4d2e-a01a-31aa0006452d] ==User Accounts of Domain Users in Acumatica ERP== After you have enabled integration with the identity management system, user accounts for domain users are created automatically when the users sign in to your Acumatica ERP instance for the first time.{br}
The accounts of domain users in Acumatica ERP are based on their accounts in the domain. The password of a domain user in Acumatica ERP is the same as the domain account password. The email address and the first and last name of the user are populated from the domain account as well. However, the login, password, email address, and first and last name are managed through the domain and cannot be changed in Acumatica ERP.((({S:Hint}You cannot restore the passwords of domain users by using Acumatica ERP tools. You should restore users&rsquo; domain credentials by using tools of Active Directory (AD). ))){br}
To speed up authentication of users, the information about AD groups is automatically cashed by Acumatica ERP, if the count of the user groups is greater than or equals to the value of the {{ADGroupCacheLimit}} parameter, specified in the <tt>web.config</tt> file. To update the list of the user groups in Acumatica ERP with current information from AD, click the '''Reload AD Groups''' button on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_05|User Roles] (201005) form. {br}
The '''Reload AD Groups''' button appears only when you integrated Acumatica ERP instance with AD, AD FS or Azure AD and when the number of the user groups in AD, AD FS or Azure AD is greater than or equals to the value of the{{ADGroupCacheLimit}} parameter, specified in the <tt>web.config</tt> file. If the number of the users and groups in AD is less than the value of the {{ADGroupCacheLimit}} parameter, Acumatica ERP retrieves the lists of users and groups directly from AD. ==Domain User Authentication== Generally, to sign in to Acumatica ERP, AD users type their domain credentials without specifying the domain name. But some employees may have both a local user account and a domain user account with the same user name. In this case, Acumatica ERP will authenticate the users based on the password they specify (assuming that the local and domain passwords differ).{br}
If both the user names and the passwords are the same for a local user account and a domain user account, on the Welcome screen, the user can select the account to sign in with as follows:[anchor|#ul_jsf_1m3_ss] *To sign in with a local account, the user enters the user name of the local account (as usual). *To sign in with a domain account, the user enters the login in the <tt>&lt;Domain&#95;Name&gt;\&lt;User&#95;Name&gt;</tt> format, where <tt>&lt;Domain&#95;Name&gt;</tt> is the NetBIOS domain name of the integrated domain and <tt>&lt;User&#95;Name&gt;</tt> is the user account name in the integrated domain. ((({S:Hint}If there is a local account with the name which includes a domain name and a user name from this domain, for example, <tt>Terra\User1</tt>, a domain user with the name ''User1'' from domain ''Terra'' will be mapped to this local account and will inherit all permissions of this account. In this case passwords of a local user and a domain user may differ but they both will access the same user account. To prevent confusion, we recommend that you disable or delete the local accounts of employees who do not perform any administration or configuration tasks in Acumatica ERP. )))[anchor|#_cef7628d-edb7-4cfe-bf22-4094aefcf3c5] ==Domain User Authorization== When a domain user tries to access Acumatica ERP, user authorization occurs as follows:[anchor|#_124a7785-41a9-4a5f-aa6b-ebfb2a60ac14] #The application instance sends an authentication request to the AD server to validate the user&rsquo;s credentials. #When validation has completed successfully, the AD server sends Acumatica ERP the list of AD groups to which the user is assigned. # Acumatica ERP compares the list of AD groups with the internal Acumatica ERP roles, based on the mapping rules defined on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_05|User Roles] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201005|SM201005]) form. #The system finds any Acumatica ERP roles that are associated with AD groups to which the domain user account is assigned. If Acumatica ERP finds at least one role, the user is authenticated to sign in to the Acumatica ERP instance. #:The user access rights within the Acumatica ERP application instance are based on the internal list of roles.
For more information about authentication in Acumatica ERP, see [HelpRoot_Administration\US__con_User_Accounts|User Accounts in Acumatica ERP]. For details about roles and access rights in Acumatica ERP, see [HelpRoot_Administration\US__con_Access_Rights|User Access Rights].[anchor|#_9a165cdb-9804-42df-8ba4-6cbc4a8698cc] ==Access Rights of Domain Users== Domain users inherit access rights from the AD groups that you mapped to Acumatica ERP user roles. In addition, you can assign specific user roles to each domain user if the access rights for this user should differ from the AD group rights.{br}
New domain users automatically get the rights to sign in to Acumatica ERP when they join a domain. The membership of these users in Acumatica ERP roles is then automatically updated to comply with the membership of the users in the domain groups.((({S:Hint}The user type functionality, described in [HelpRoot_Administration\US__con_User_Accounts#_775858a7-972a-4226-ac5d-7e74ae894419|User Types] , cannot be applied to domain users. ))) ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_Administration\US__con_User_Accounts|User Accounts in Acumatica ERP] *[HelpRoot_Administration\US__con_Access_Rights|User Access Rights] *[HelpRoot_Integration\US__how_Active_Directory_Integration__Enable|To Enable Active Directory Integration] *[HelpRoot_Integration\US__how_Active_Directory_Integration__Map_Roles|To Map Active Directory Groups to Roles in Acumatica ERP] *[HelpRoot_Integration\US__how_AD_Groups_Override|To Set Up Role Assignment for Domain Users] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_05|User Roles] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201005|SM201005])

You integrate Acumatica ERP with Microsoft Active Directory Federation Services (AD FS) when you want to manage users and access rights using Active Directory (AD) and your Acumatica ERP instance is deployed on the Internet but not in your organization&rsquo;s intranet. Integration of Acumatica ERP with AD FS also provides single sign-on for domain users between your Acumatica ERP instance and other services that use AD FS.{br}{TOC} ==Requirements== To seamlessly integrate your AD FS server and your Acumatica ERP instance, make sure that the following requirements are met.[anchor|#ul_slg_xpd_ss] *The AD FS version is 2012 R2 (included in Windows Server 2012 R2). *AD FS is configured to provide access to external web services. *The domain users have preconfigured email addresses.
==Configuration Steps== You can configure integration with AD FS when you implement Acumatica ERP or at any later time. To integrate an instance of Acumatica ERP with AD FS, you perform the following steps:[anchor|#ol_hfn_dbq_z4] #Configure the AD FS server. Do the following: ##Configure AD FS Relying Party Trust to register your Acumatica ERP instance with AD FS. For details, see [HelpRoot_Integration\US__how_ADFS_Configure_ADFS_relying_party_trust|To Configure the AD FS Relying Party Trust]. ##Configure claims for Acumatica ERP, as described in [HelpRoot_Integration\US__how_ADFS_Configure_ADFS_Claims|To Configure AD FS Claims]. #Enable integration with AD FS by modifying the <tt>web.config</tt> file of the application instance, as described in [HelpRoot_Integration\US__how_ADFS_Enable_Integration|To Enable AD FS Integration with Acumatica ERP]. #:((({S:Warn}When you save changes to the <tt>web.config</tt> file, the website is automatically restarted. Make sure that all users are warned about the restart so that they can save their documents in advance. ))) #Map the AD FS claims to Acumatica ERP roles. This process is described in [HelpRoot_Integration\US__how_ADFS_map_claims|To Map AD FS Claims to Roles in Acumatica ERP] . #Optional: If required, override the roles assigned to any user automatically by selecting the required roles manually. For details, see [HelpRoot_Integration\US__how_ADFS_Groups_Override|To Set Up Role Assignment for Domain Users]. #Optional: If you want to use the AD FS service as the default identity provider, enable silent logon with AD FS, as described in [HelpRoot_Integration\US__how_ADFS_Silent_Logon_Enable|To Enable Silent Logon]. [anchor|#_ac143a80-0bd3-4fca-b0aa-d771fa28a9c0] ==User Accounts of Domain Users in Acumatica ERP== After you have enabled integration with the identity management system, user accounts for domain users are created automatically when the users sign in to your Acumatica ERP instance for the first time.{br}
The accounts of domain users in Acumatica ERP are based on their accounts in the domain. The password of a domain user in Acumatica ERP is the same as the domain account password. The email address and the first and last name of the user are populated from the domain account as well. However, the login, password, email address, and first and last name are managed through the domain and cannot be changed in Acumatica ERP.((({S:Hint}You cannot restore the passwords of domain users by using Acumatica ERP tools. You should restore users&rsquo; domain credentials by using tools of Active Directory (AD). ))){br}
To speed up authentication of users, the information about AD groups is automatically cashed by Acumatica ERP, if the count of the user groups is greater than or equals to the value of the {{ADGroupCacheLimit}} parameter, specified in the <tt>web.config</tt> file. To update the list of the user groups in Acumatica ERP with current information from AD, click the '''Reload AD Groups''' button on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_05|User Roles] (201005) form. {br}
The '''Reload AD Groups''' button appears only when you integrated Acumatica ERP instance with AD, AD FS or Azure AD and when the number of the user groups in AD, AD FS or Azure AD is greater than or equals to the value of the{{ADGroupCacheLimit}} parameter, specified in the <tt>web.config</tt> file. If the number of the users and groups in AD is less than the value of the {{ADGroupCacheLimit}} parameter, Acumatica ERP retrieves the lists of users and groups directly from AD. ==Domain User Authentication== After integration of Acumatica ERP with AD FS users use single sign-on (SSO) with the domain to sign in to Acumatica ERP. By default, the users do the following to authenticate themselves:[anchor|#ol_u3b_wdk_ss] #On the '''Welcome''' page of your Acumatica ERP instance, the user selects the Azure AD icon ([image:UserGuide/Images/AD_AzureAD.png|12px]) to open the AD FS sign-in page. #On the sign-in page, the user enters the domain credentials in the following format: <tt>&lt;User&#95;Name&gt;@&lt;Domain&#95;Name&gt;</tt>, where ''&lt;User&#95;Name&gt;'' is the user account name in the integrated domain and ''&lt;Domain&#95;Name&gt;'' is the UPN suffix, also known as the domain name.
To simplify the procedure, you can configure silent logon with the AD FS server. For more information, see [HelpRoot_Integration\US__how_ADFS_Silent_Logon_Enable|To Enable Silent Logon].[anchor|#_eeb681e5-ae8f-4c30-9e2d-521afca37a6a]((({S:Hint}If you configured a multi-company instance and selected the '''Secure Company on Login''' option on the '''Company Setup''' page (see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Support_of_Multiple_Companies|Support of Multiple Tenants]), then users with access to several companies, who sign in to Acumatica ERP using single sign-on with an external identity provider, will be logged in to the first company with enabled single sign-on. )))[anchor|#_49b02f1d-b644-4af5-8e13-f22dd69b651d] ==Domain User Authorization== When a domain user tries to access Acumatica ERP, user authorization occurs as follows:[anchor|#_a757d57b-2cef-44d4-a1ab-de7aaf941ace] #The application instance sends an authentication request to the AD server to validate the user&rsquo;s credentials. #When validation has completed successfully, the AD server sends Acumatica ERP the list of AD groups to which the user is assigned. # Acumatica ERP compares the list of AD groups with the internal Acumatica ERP roles, based on the mapping rules defined on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_05|User Roles] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201005|SM201005]) form. #The system finds any Acumatica ERP roles that are associated with AD groups to which the domain user account is assigned. If Acumatica ERP finds at least one role, the user is authenticated to sign in to the Acumatica ERP instance. #:The user access rights within the Acumatica ERP application instance are based on the internal list of roles.
For more information about authentication in Acumatica ERP, see [HelpRoot_Administration\US__con_User_Accounts|User Accounts in Acumatica ERP]. For details about roles and access rights in Acumatica ERP, see [HelpRoot_Administration\US__con_Access_Rights|User Access Rights].[anchor|#_9305689c-2e75-45e8-8c20-70ada9130ed6] ==Access Rights of Domain Users== Domain users inherit access rights from the AD groups that you mapped to Acumatica ERP user roles. In addition, you can assign specific user roles to each domain user if the access rights for this user should differ from the AD group rights.{br}
New domain users automatically get the rights to sign in to Acumatica ERP when they join a domain. The membership of these users in Acumatica ERP roles is then automatically updated to comply with the membership of the users in the domain groups.((({S:Hint}The user type functionality, described in [HelpRoot_Administration\US__con_User_Accounts#_775858a7-972a-4226-ac5d-7e74ae894419|User Types] , cannot be applied to domain users. ))) ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Support_of_Multiple_Companies|Support of Multiple Tenants] *[HelpRoot_Administration\US__con_Access_Rights|User Access Rights] *[HelpRoot_Administration\US__con_User_Accounts|User Accounts in Acumatica ERP] *[HelpRoot_Integration\US__how_ADFS_Configure_ADFS_relying_party_trust|To Configure the AD FS Relying Party Trust] *[HelpRoot_Integration\US__how_ADFS_Configure_ADFS_Claims|To Configure AD FS Claims] *[HelpRoot_Integration\US__how_ADFS_Enable_Integration|To Enable AD FS Integration with Acumatica ERP] *[HelpRoot_Integration\US__how_ADFS_map_claims|To Map AD FS Claims to Roles in Acumatica ERP] *[HelpRoot_Integration\US__how_ADFS_Groups_Override|To Set Up Role Assignment for Domain Users] *[HelpRoot_Integration\US__how_ADFS_Silent_Logon_Enable|To Enable Silent Logon] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_05|User Roles] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201005|SM201005])

