==Date/Time Functions==
The date and time functions, described below, perform operations on input values and return values of the following types: string, numeric, or date and time. 
{| class="checklist" | width="100%" 
|- 
!width="20%" ! Function
!width="80%" ! Description and Example
|- 
| <tt>DateAdd(date, interval, number)</tt>
| [anchor|#_d1185d45-1e88-4eb5-b088-b38bec488e43]
Returns a new date that is calculated by adding the specified number (<tt>number</tt>) of time intervals (<tt>interval</tt>) to the date (<tt>date</tt>). The <tt>interval</tt> argument specifies the type of time interval and can be one of the following options: [anchor|#_a1020b33-55e0-46c6-b1ee-05d07390e9a9]
*''y'': The specified number (<tt>number</tt>) of years will be added to the specified date (<tt>date</tt>). 
*''m'': The specified number (<tt>number</tt>) of months will be added to the specified date (<tt>date</tt>).
*''d'': The specified number (<tt>number</tt>) of days will be added to the specified date (<tt>date</tt>).
*''h'': The specified number (<tt>number</tt>) of hours will be added to the specified date (<tt>date</tt>).
*''n'': The specified number (<tt>number</tt>) of minutes will be added to the specified date (<tt>date</tt>).
*''s'': The specified number (<tt>number</tt>) of seconds will be added to the specified date (<tt>date</tt>).
*''w'' or ''ww'': The specified number (<tt>number</tt>) of weeks will be added to the specified date (<tt>date</tt>).
*''q'': The specified number (<tt>number</tt>) of quarters will be added to the specified date (<tt>date</tt>).
{br}

Consider the following examples:[anchor|#_90aff076-4151-4378-a6f2-baca56071ea1]
*{{=DateAdd([StartPeriod], 'm', 12)}}
*{{=DateAdd([CashDiscountDate], 'd', -2)}}
{br}

In these examples, {{[CashDiscountDate]}} and {{[StartPeriod]}} are the fields that are used as the function arguments.
|- 
| <tt>DateDiff(interval, date1, date2)</tt>
| [anchor|#_30b819a1-5fa5-47de-bb4c-ae8b09276670]
Returns the number of time intervals (<tt>interval</tt>) between the specified <tt>date1</tt> and <tt>date2</tt>. The number is an integer that can be positive or negative. The <tt>interval</tt> argument, which specifies the type of time interval, can be one of the following options: [anchor|#_bb6a04cb-2167-4427-b85e-79695a1ce2e4]
*''y'': The specified number (<tt>number</tt>) of years will be added to the specified date (<tt>date</tt>). 
*''m'': The specified number (<tt>number</tt>) of months will be added to the specified date (<tt>date</tt>).
*''d'': The specified number (<tt>number</tt>) of days will be added to the specified date (<tt>date</tt>).
*''h'': The specified number (<tt>number</tt>) of hours will be added to the specified date (<tt>date</tt>).
*''n'': The specified number (<tt>number</tt>) of minutes will be added to the specified date (<tt>date</tt>).
*''s'': The specified number (<tt>number</tt>) of seconds will be added to the specified date (<tt>date</tt>).
*''w'' or ''ww'': The specified number (<tt>number</tt>) of weeks will be added to the specified date (<tt>date</tt>).
*''q'': The specified number (<tt>number</tt>) of quarters will be added to the specified date (<tt>date</tt>).
{br}

Consider the following example: {{=DateDiff('d', CDate('3/12/2018'), CDate('4/12/2018'))}}
|- 
| <tt>Day(date)</tt>
| 
Returns the day (as an integer) extracted from the specified date (<tt>date</tt>).{br}

Consider the following example: {{=Iif(Day([DueDate]-[LeadTime])=0, True, False }}{br}

Here {{[DueDate]}} and {{[LeadTime]}} are used in the function argument.
|- 
| <tt>DayOfWeek(date)</tt>
