Returns the day of the week associated with the specified date (<tt>date</tt>) as an integer.{br}

Consider the following example: {{=DayOfWeek([StartPeriod])}}{br}

Here {{[StartPeriod]}} is used as the function argument.
|- 
| <tt>DayOfYear(date)</tt>
| 
Returns the day of the year calculated for the specified date (<tt>date</tt>).{br}

Consider the following example: {{=DayOfYear([StartPeriod])}}{br}

Here {{[StartPeriod]}} is used as the function argument.
|- 
| <tt>DayOrdinal(day)</tt>
| [anchor|#_ec832f69-a88c-4f8b-908b-2d5b87abe933]
Converts the specified integer value (<tt>day</tt>) to a string that contains the ordinal number in the current locale. For example, for the English locale, the string contains the short form of the ordinal number, such as 1st or 2nd. For numbers that are less than 1 or greater than 31, the function returns an empty string.{br}

Consider the following example: {{=DayOrdinal(1)}}
|- 
| <tt>Hour(date)</tt>
| 
Returns the hours extracted from the specified date (<tt>date</tt>).{br}

